{"id":"1608.03586","submitter":"Rong-Qiang He","authors":"Rong-Qiang He and Zhong-Yi Lu","title":"Characterizing Many-Body Localization by Out-of-Time-Ordered Correlation","comments":"5 pages, 4 figures; improved; published version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 95, 054201 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.95.054201","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The out-of-time-ordered (OTO) correlation is a key quantity for quantifying\nquantum chaoticity and has been recently used in the investigation of quantum\nholography. Here we use it to study and characterize many-body localization\n(MBL). We find that a long-time logarithmic variation of the OTO correlation\noccurs in the MBL phase but is absent in the Anderson localized and ergodic\nphases. We extract a localization length in the MBL phase, which depends\nlogarithmically on interaction and diverges at a critical interaction.\nFurthermore, the infinite-time `thermal' fluctuation of the OTO correlation is\nzero (finite) in the ergodic (MBL) phase and thus can be considered as an order\nparameter for the ergodic-MBL transition, through which the transition can be\nidentified and characterized. Specifically, the critical point and the related\ncritical exponents can be calculated.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 Aug 2016 19:59:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 12 Feb 2017 17:02:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-02-15"}
